{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1954 | birth_place = | alma_mater = | institution = [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] | death_date = | death_place = | religion = [[Hinduism]] | occupation = Writer, academic | nationality = Indian | period = | genre = | influences = | signature = | website = }}
'''Meera Nanda''' (born 1954) is an Indian writer and [[philosopher of science]] based in the United States,<ref name=three/> who has authored several works critiquing the influence of [[Hindutva]], [[postcolonialism]] and [[postmodernism]] on science, and the flourishing of [[pseudoscience]] and [[Vedanga|vedic science]].
== Life and career ==
Nanda was educated in science and philosophy with a PhD in [[biotechnology]] from the [[Indian Institute of Technology, Delhi]] and a PhD in science studies from [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]].<ref>[http://calendar.iisc.ernet.in/abstract.php?mid=MID201018179 Reception of Darwinism in India (A talk by Professor Meera Nanda)], Indian Institute of Science</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mukto-mona.com/wordpress/?author=38|title=Mukto-Mona Writers' Corner - Meera Nanda|website=mukto-mona.com}}</ref>
She was a [[John Templeton Foundation]] Fellow in Religion and Science (2005–2007).<ref name=three>[http://www.threeessays.com/authors.php?id=4 Meera Nanda Profile] Three Essays.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In defence of secularism|url=http://www.hindu.com/br/2006/11/21/stories/2006112100521400.htm |author= [[Ranjit Hoskote]]| publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=21 November 2006}}</ref> In January 2009, she was a Fellow at the Jawaharlal Nehru Institute for Advanced Study, in the [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] for research in Science, Post-Modernism and Culture.<ref>[http://www.jnu.ac.in/JNIAS/Scholars_invited.htm List of scholars invited to JNIAS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716191040/http://www.jnu.ac.in/jnias/Scholars_invited.htm |date=16 July 2010 }} JNIAS [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] website.</ref> She was also a visiting faculty of history and philosophy of science at [[Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Mohali]] from 2010 to 15 May 2017.
==Religion and Hindu nationalism== {{too few opinions|section|date=October 2016}}
Nanda has authored several works on religion, most notably ''Prophets Facing Backward: Postmodern Critiques of Science and Hindu Nationalism in India'' (2004),<ref>{{cite news |title=Book Review: Paradigm shift |url=http://www.hindu.com/br/2005/05/03/stories/2005050300281600.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |author= [[Ranjit Hoskote]]|date=3 May 2005}}</ref> and her 2009 book ''The God Market'' which examined how India is experiencing a rising tide of popular Hinduism, including [[Indian government|government]] financing of [[Hinduism]] despite the nation's secular characteristic. The book was also reviewed by [[William Dalrymple (historian)|William Dalrymple]] in ''[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook Magazine]]''.<ref name=glitter>{{cite web|title=Review: The Glitter in The Godliness|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?263657|publisher=[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook]]|accessdate=8 September 2013|author=William Dalrymple|authorlink=William Dalrymple (historian)|date=18 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Books: A market for holy men: How globalization has had an impact on Hinduism and our public sphere |url= http://www.livemint.com/2009/08/21210545/A-market-for-holy-men.html?h=B|publisher=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]] |date=21 August 2009}}</ref>
Nanda notes the popularity of yoga exercises in the west, and the discomfort of Indians with this popularisation, who "blame Americans and other 'decadent' Westerners for reducing their spiritually rich tradition to mere calisthenics."<ref name="Not as old"/> Yet, she questions the idea that yoga is a "timeless" and "eternal" practice, which lies at the heart of Hinduism.<ref name="Not as old">Meera Nanda, [http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/living/not-as-old-as-you-think ''Yoga. Not as Old as You Think''], OPEN 12 February 2011</ref> She has criticised the Hindu American Foundation (HAF) for {{quote|The purist Hindu position [...] that all yoga, including its physical or hatha yoga component, is rooted in the Hindu religion/way of life that goes all the way back to the Vedic sages and [[yogi]]s.<ref name="Not as old"/>}}
Nanda notes that the yoga asanas do not have Vedic origins, and were treated with disdain by the 19th century Hindu elites, including Swami Vivekananda. She further notes that the separation of the physical practices from their cultural background started in India, not in the west, when Indian nationalists tried to counter western influences and {{quote|... hatha yoga took on many elements of Western gymnastics and body-building, which show up in the world-renowned Iyengar and Ashtanga Vinyasa schools of yoga. Far from honestly acknowledging the Western contributions to modern yoga, we Indians simply brand all yoga as ‘Vedic,’ a smug claim that has no intellectual integrity.<ref name="Not as old"/>}}
HAF rebutted her claims in a reply which pointed out that even the few sources she mentions in her book such as Mark Singleton, have themselves not made the claims that she ascribes them to. HAF also presented a brief outline of the recorded history of yoga, which disproved her arguments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hafsite.org/whats-new/open-magazine-features-haf-yoga-piece-audacity-ignorance|title=OPEN Magazine features HAF Yoga Piece: The Audacity of Ignorance|website=Hindu American Foundation (HAF)}}</ref>
Her critique has been rejected by the Hindu American Foundation. Swaminathan Venkataraman, of the [[Hindu American Foundation]], alleged that Nanda harboured "hatred" for [[Swami Vivekananda]], and that she feared the emergence of an articulate Hindu voice bringing Hindu perspectives into the public sphere.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.openthemagazine.com/article/international/disguised-hinduphobia|title= Disguised Hinduphobia|author= Swaminathan Venkataraman|date= 7 March 2011|publisher= OPEN Magazine|accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> [[Rajiv Malhotra]] criticised her for denouncing Indian culture and painting [[Hinduism]] as anti-scientific while allegedly praising [[Protestantism]] as scientific.<ref name=leftwing>{{cite book |first1=Rajiv |last1=Malhotra |authorlink1=Rajiv Malhotra |first2=Aravindan |last2=Neelakandan |title=Breaking India: Western Interventions in Dravidian and Dalit Faultlines |publisher=Amaryllis |year=2011 |ISBN=8191067374 |chapter=India: A left-wing frontier}}</ref>
However, Nanda has pointed out that her criticism was equally applicable to all "resurgent religious-political movements" not only among Hindus, but also Christians and Muslims. The Bush White House's recruitment of Christian evangelicals and corporate scientists to shape policies on issues such as open support for Biblical Flood geology and stem cell research was very similar to the state support for Vedic astrology by the Hindu nationalists.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Meera |last=Nanda |year=2005 |title=Response to my critics |journal=Social Epistemology: A Journal of Knowledge, Culture and Policy |volume=19 |number=1 |pp=147–191 |DOI=10.1080/02691720500084358}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Postmodernism and Religious Fundamentalism: A Scientific Rebuttal To Hindu Science''. New Delhi: Navayana. 2000. {{ISBN|81-89059-02-5}} * ''Breaking the Spell of Dharma and Other Essays''. New Delhi: Three Essays Collective, 2002. {{ISBN|81-88394-09-2}}. * ''Prophets Facing Backward: Postmodern Critiques of Science and the Hindu Nationalism in India''. New Brunswick: Rutgers University Press, 2004. {{ISBN|81-7824-090-4}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=h3mUi5Uan_UC&pg=PA42&dq=Meera+Nanda+writer&cd=1#v=onepage&q=&f=false Excerpts] * ''Wrongs of the Religious Right: Reflections on secularism, science and Hindutva''. New Delhi: Three Essays Collective, 2005. {{ISBN|81-88789-30-5}} * ''The God Market''. Random House, 2010. {{ISBN|81-8400-095-2}}. * ''Ayurveda Today : A Critical Look'', with C. Viswanathan. Penguin, 2010. {{ISBN|9780143065128}}. * ''Science in Saffron: Skeptical Essays on History of Science''. New Delhi: Three Essays Collective, 2016. {{ISBN|978-93-83968-08-4}}.<ref>{{citation |first=Meera |last=Nanda |title=Hindutva’s science envy |url=http://www.frontline.in/science-and-technology/hindutvas-science-envy/article9049883.ece |newspaper=Frontline |date=16 September 2016 |accessdate=14 October 2016}} </ref>
