'''Najm al-Dīn al-Qazwīnī al-Kātibī''' (died AH 675 / 1276 CE) was a [[Persian people|Persian]] [[Islamic]] [[Islamic philosophy|philosopher]] and [[Logic in Islamic philosophy|logician]] of the [[Shafi`i]] school.<ref name=EI2>{{Cite encyclopedia| edition = New| publisher = [[E. J. Brill]]| isbn = 90-04-05745-5| volume = 4| pages = 762a–b| editor = E. van Donzel |display-editors=etal| last = Mohaghegh| first = M.| title = al-Kātibī, Najm al-Dīn Abu'l-Ḥasan ʿAlī b. ʿUmar| encyclopedia = The Encyclopaedia of Islam| location = Leiden| date = 1978}}</ref> A student of [[Athīr al-Dīn al-Abharī]].<ref name=EI2 /> His most important works are a treatise on logic, ''Al-Risala al-Shamsiyya'', and one on [[Islamic metaphysics|metaphysics]] and the natural sciences, ''Hikmat al-'Ain''.<ref>Page 227 of {{Cite book | publisher = Brill | isbn = 978-90-04-12978-8 | editor = David C. Reisman | editor2 = Ahmed H. al-Rahim | last = al-Rahim | first = Ahmed H. | title = Before and After Avicenna: Proceedings of the First Conference of the Avicenna Study Group | chapter = The Twelver Si'i Reception of Avicenna in the Mongol Period | series = Islamic philosophy, theology and science: texts and studies | date = 2003 }}</ref>
He helped establish the [[Maragha observatory]] along with [[Nasir al-Din al-Tusi]] and several other astronomers.<ref name=EI2 />
==Logic== His work on logic, the ''al-Risāla al-Shamsiyya'' (''Logic for Shams al-Dīn''), was commonly used as the first major text on logic in [[madrasah]]s, right down until the twentieth century and is "perhaps the most studied logic textbook of all time".<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | isbn = 978-0-521-52069-0 | editor = Peter Adamson | editor2 = Richard C. Taylor | last = Street | first = Tony | title = The Cambridge Companion to Arabic Philosophy | chapter = Logic | date = 2005 | pages = 247–265, 247 & 250 }}</ref> Al-Katibi's logic was largely inspired by the formal [[Avicennian logic|Avicennian system]] of [[Temporal logic|temporal]] [[modal logic]], but is more elaborate and departs from it in several ways. While Avicenna considered ten modalities and examined six of them, al-Katibi considers many more modalized propositions and examines thirteen which he considers 'customary to investigate'.<ref>{{citation|title=Toward a History of Syllogistic After Avicenna: Notes on Rescher's Studies on Arabic Modal Logic|author=Tony Street|journal=Journal of Islamic Studies|volume=11|issue=2|date=2000|pages=209–228}}</ref>
